497.title: Symmetric group
497.clickbait: The symmetric groups form the fundamental link between group theory and the notion of symmetry.
497.text:
The notion that group theory captures the idea of "symmetry" derives from the notion of the symmetric group, and the very important theorem due to Cayley that every group is a subgroup of a symmetric group.

# Definition

Let $X$ be a [-3jz]. A [bijective_function bijection] $f: X \to X$ is a *permutation* of $X$.
Write $\mathrm{Sym}(X)$ for the set of permutations of the set $X$ (so its elements are functions).

Then $\mathrm{Sym}(X)$ is a group under the operation of composition of functions; it is the *symmetric group on $X$*.

We write $S_n$ for $\mathrm{Sym}(\{ 1,2, \dots, n\})$, the *symmetric group on $n$ elements*.

# Elements of $S_n$

We can represent a permutation of $\{1,2,\dots, n\}$ in two different ways, each of which is useful in different situations.

## Double-row notation

Let $\sigma \in S_n$, so $\sigma$ is a function $\{1,2,\dots,n\} \to \{1,2,\dots,n\}$.
Then we write $$\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & \dots & n \\ \sigma(1) & \sigma(2) & \dots & \sigma(n) \\ \end{pmatrix}$$
for $\sigma$.
This has the advantage that it is immediately clear where every element goes, but the disadvantage that it is quite hard to see the properties of an element when it is written in double-row notation (for example, "$\sigma$ cycles round five elements" is hard to spot at a glance), and it is not very compact.

## Cycle notation

[todo: perhaps "cycle" should be its own page, with properties such as "inverse" and "order".]

A $k$-cycle is a member of $S_n$ which moves $k$ elements to each other cyclically.
That is, letting $a_1, \dots, a_k$ be distinct in $\{1,2,\dots,n\}$, a $k$-cycle $\sigma$ is such that $\sigma(a_i) = a_{i+1}$ for $1 \leq i < k$, and $\sigma(a_k) = a_1$, and $\sigma(x) = x$ for any $x \not \in \{a_1, \dots, a_k \}$.

We have a much more compact notation for $\sigma$ in this case: we write $\sigma = (a_1 a_2 \dots a_k)$.
(If spacing is ambiguous, we put in commas: $\sigma = (a_1, a_2, \dots, a_k)$.)
Note that there are several ways to write this: $(a_1 a_2 \dots a_k) = (a_2 a_3 \dots a_k a_1)$, for example.
It is conventional to put the smallest $a_i$ at the start.

Note also that a cycle's inverse is extremely easy to find: the inverse of $(a_1 a_2 \dots a_k)$ is $(a_k a_{k-1} \dots a_1)$.

For example, the double-row notation $$\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 \\ 2 & 3 & 1 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$
is written as $(123)$ or $(231)$ or $(312)$ in cycle notation.

Not every element of $S_n$ is a cycle. For example, the following element of $S_4$ has order $2$ so could only be a $2$-cycle, but it moves all four elements:
$$\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ 2 & 1 & 4 & 3 \\ \end{pmatrix}$$

However, it may be written as the composition of the two cycles $(12)$ and $(34)$: it is the result of applying one and then the other.
Note that since the cycles are disjoint (having no elements in common), it doesn't matter in which order we perform them. [todo: create a separate page proving this.]
It is a very important fact that every permutation may be written as the product of disjoint cycles. [todo: create separate page proving this.]

# Examples

- The group $S_1$ is the group of permutations of a one-point set. It contains the identity only, so $S_1$ is the trivial group.
- The group $S_2$ is isomorphic to the [-47y] of order $2$. It contains the identity map and the map which interchanges $1$ and $2$.

Those are the only two [3h2 abelian] symmetric groups.

49f.title: Cycle notation in symmetric groups

49g.title: Disjoint cycles commute in symmetric groups
49g.clickbait: In cycle notation, if two cycles are disjoint, then they commute.

4bh.title: Conjugacy class is cycle type in symmetric group
4bh.clickbait: There is a neat characterisation of the conjugacy classes in the symmetric group on a finite set.

4bj.title: Conjugacy class
4bj.clickbait: In a group, the elements can be partitioned naturally into certain classes.

4bk.title: Conjugacy classes of the symmetric group on five elements
4bk.clickbait: The symmetric group on five elements is a group of just the right size to make a good example of a table of conjugacy classes.

4cg.title: Cycle type of a permutation
4cg.clickbait: The cycle type is an invariant of a permutation in the symmetric group.

4cn.title: Transposition (as an element of a symmetric group)
4cn.clickbait: A transposition is the simplest kind of permutation: it swaps two elements.

4cp.title: Every member of a symmetric group on finitely many elements is a product of transpositions
4cp.clickbait: This fact can often simplify arguments about permutations: if we can show that something holds for transpositions, and that it holds for products, then it holds for everything.

4cy.title: Dihedral group
4cy.clickbait: The dihedral groups are natural examples of groups, arising from the symmetries of regular polygons.

4h6.title: Normal subgroup
4h6.clickbait: Normal subgroups are subgroups which are in some sense "the same from all points of view".

4hf.title: Alternating group
4hf.clickbait: The alternating group is the only normal subgroup of the symmetric group (on five or more generators).

4hg.title: The collection of even-signed permutations is a group
4hg.clickbait: This proves the well-definedness of one particular definition of the alternating group.

4hh.title: The sign of a permutation is well-defined
4hh.clickbait: This result is what allows the alternating group to exist.

4hk.title: Sign homomorphism (from the symmetric group)
4hk.clickbait: The sign homomorphism is how we extract the alternating group from the symmetric group.
